# TASK
Create a single, self-contained PowerShell audit script for ONE specific CIS
benchmark version: **CIS Microsoft Windows Server [2022 | 2025] Benchmark**,
targeting the **Domain Controller** profile. The script is NOT dynamic — all
check data is hardcoded into the script. I will attach the official CIS
benchmark PDF; extract everything from that PDF, not from your training data.

# CRITICAL CONSTRAINTS
1. READ-ONLY. The script must only read system state. It may use ONLY:
   - Get-ItemProperty (registry reads)
   - secedit /export (NEVER /configure or /import)
   - auditpol /get (NEVER /set)
   - Get-CimInstance (host/role info)
   The only writes permitted are: creating the output report folder, and a
   temp file for the secedit export that is deleted after reading. No
   Set-ItemProperty, New-ItemProperty, Remove-Item (except that temp file),
   reg add/delete, Set-Service, or GPO cmdlets anywhere.

2. NO external dependencies on the target server: no PDF, no Microsoft Word,
   no third-party tools, no internet. All check data is baked into the script.

3. ACCURACY OVER COVERAGE. Do not guess registry value names or expected
   values from memory. Extract each one from the attached PDF's "Audit:"
   section. The CIS PDF wraps long registry paths and value names across
   lines — reassemble them carefully (e.g. a path segment like "Windows NT"
   legitimately contains a space; a value name split as "ConsentPromptB" +
   "ehaviorAdmin" must be rejoined to "ConsentPromptBehaviorAdmin"). If you
   cannot confidently determine a value name or expected value, DO NOT invent
   one — classify that recommendation as "Needs Review" and include its
   benchmark page number so I can verify it manually.

# SCOPE
Include every recommendation that applies to the Domain Controller profile.
Exclude Member-Server-only recommendations (those marked "(MS only)", or whose
Profile Applicability lists only "Member Server" with no "Domain Controller").
Include "(DC only)" items and items with no role marker.

# ENGINES — route each recommendation to the correct check method:
- Registry (HKLM)  → most of sections 2.3, 9, 18 (Get-ItemProperty)
- Registry (HKCU)  → section 19 / per-user policies (read current-user hive)
- secedit          → section 1 (password/lockout: map titles to INF keys like
                     PasswordHistorySize, MaximumPasswordAge, LockoutBadCount…)
- secedit (URA)    → section 2.2 User Rights (map titles to privilege constants
                     like SeNetworkLogonRight, SeDenyInteractiveLogonRight…).
                     Report the assigned accounts and mark "Needs Review" — do
                     NOT auto-resolve SID-to-name, which causes false results.
- auditpol         → section 17 Advanced Audit Policy (subcategory + Success/
                     Failure/both)
- Needs Review     → multi-string values, special controls, or anything you
                     can't confidently automate

# REGISTRY COMPARISON OPERATORS to support:
eq (exact), ge ("N or more"), le ("N or fewer"), le_not0 ("N or fewer but not
0"), in (list like "1 or 2"), between ("between 5 and 14"), absent ("a value
does not exist"). Normalize hive prefixes (HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE → HKLM, etc.).

# SCRIPT STRUCTURE
- Comment-based help header (.SYNOPSIS/.DESCRIPTION/.NOTES) stating it is
  read-only and listing requirements (run elevated; PowerShell 5.1+).
- Hardcoded check tables as arrays of hashtables, one array per engine, each
  entry carrying: Id, Title, the engine-specific fields, Expected value, and
  the benchmark Page number.
- Read-only engine functions (registry/secedit/auditpol) as shown above.
- A self-audit transcript log that records every action taken (every path
  read, actual vs expected value, and verdict), proving the read-only claim.
- Outputs to a folder on the Desktop: a CSV report, a color-coded HTML report
  (green=Configured, red=Not Configured, amber=Needs Review, with the
  benchmark page number shown on each row), and the transcript log.
- Console summary: counts of Configured / Not Configured / Needs Review and a
  compliance % of assessable checks.

# OUTPUT FORMAT
- Provide the complete .ps1 as a single code block.
- Before the script, give a short coverage summary: how many recommendations
